beer_brewer_name: Vermont Hard Cider Company, LLC (C&C; Group)
review_blob: Great apple flavors, best served ice cold for my taste.  Not the best cider out there, but close to the top on my list.
Had to give it a try again after all these years.  Now I'm wondering, of course, why I bothered.
I must agree with some of the other comments regarding appearance.  Not all together a bad looking beer.  Taste is what you would expect though for a product from this company.
A great looking beer with an excellent pour, but otherwise rather disappointing.
Nice darker brown color.  Medium head, with little lace.  Decent malt flavors, with a little too much sweetness.  Not as good as I remember, but then those were the college years.
Even worse than regular Busch, if thats possible.  Its amazing what some advertising can do for a beer.
Advertising, Advertising, Advertising.  Cant add much more to whats already been written below.
Slightly better than the standard Mexican beer.  Dark color, faint aroma, watery mouthfeel.  A litle too sweet for my tastes.
Beautiful brown amber color, with creamy head.  Excellent lacing.  Not quite as good as Chimay, but definitely worth a try.
Nothing remarkable here.  I must admit I never did like this beer, and after giving it another shot here lately, it has done nothing to change my mind.
Nice golden color, with a quickly disappearing head.  Not a bad beer, just nothing remarkable.

Nice amber colors with a decent head.  Aroma of fruit and spice. Very well balanced flavor, with a hint of spices and malts. The alcohol is well hidden. I prefer the Bleu, but this is definitely worth a try.
Nice blackish brown in color.  Thick, creamy brown head with plenty of lace.  Nice malt, oatmeal flavors with hops in the finish.  Still prefer Samuel Smiths, but this definitely worth a try.

2002 Bottle. Nice dark reddish color with medium off white head. Aroma abound with plenty of nutmeg and spices. Flavor is strong with nutmeg, with a hint of chocolate?  Finished sweet with mild bitterness and lingering spices with nutmeg.  Different yet pleasing to my palate.
Nice amber color.  Small white head with a little lacing.  Not the usual spicyness that I enjoy.  Not bad overall.
Nice deep mahoghany color.  Decent head with plenty of lace.  Malty aroma.  Excellent tastes.  Im glad I tried the Bleu version.
Ugh.  I doubt there is anything more I can add to the comments below.
A step above Bud light and step below Bud Ice.  Im in agreement with the Snapple comment below.
Only slightly better than regular Bud.
Just your average American Pilsener.  Drinkable, but nothing remarkable here.
Nice amber color with off whitish head.  Floral, malty aroma.  Decent flavor but a little too much bitter for my taste.

beer_brewer_name: Portland Brewing Company (Pyramid - North American Breweries)
review_blob: Nice copper color.  Medium, thin head.  Standard caramelly aroma.  Nice flavor, but certainly not the best of its class.
Nice frothy head, with plenty of lace.  Citrusy aromas abound.  Fruity, spicy taste.  Very drinkable.
Not a whole lot going on here.  A slight grade above the standard American beers, but not by much.
Nice orange color with a white, quickly fading head.  Excellent flavor and aroma.  I prefer a slightly more bitter finish.
Dry and crisp with a clean flavor.  Not a whole lot going on here.
Nice hops with citrus overtones.  A standard among Pale Ales.  Still a beer I find myself reaching for when looking for something reliable.
Certainly weaker than the original.  The only redeeming grace is the lime that comes with it.
What can you say about a beer that only tastes good with lime added??
I see nothing more I can add to the comments below.
Light flavor with the dry finish you would expect.  A notch below the regular and dark lines of Michelob.
Probably one of the better American standard beers.  One click below their Dark product in my book.
Nice color and thats about it.  Maybe just one step above regular Michelob.
I guess this beer serves its purpose for the low carb crowd, but thats about it.
I seem to remember this beer being better.  Or maybe my tastes have just changed.  I found the flavor light this go around and generally unremarkable.
Light gold, with a small head.  Taste and flavor were both mild.  Seems to be hit or miss with this one.
A click above Miller Lite and click below Miller High Life for my tastes.  One has to wonder if they wouldnt be better off drinking a nice glass of water.
For my tastes this is better than MGD or Miller Lite, but not by much.
After reading all the comments below, I dont believe there is anything else I can add.
Light golden amber color.  Medium head.  Slight hint of hops with mild citrus flavors.  Someone mentioned "hefe-light"--I couldnt agree more.
Light gold in color.  Nicely rounded malt flavors.  Fairly crisp finish.  Not a bad lager.
Light gold in color.  Small white head with decent lace.  Light body and taste.  Finish was clean.
Nice reddish/amber color.  Decent medium head.  Light body, mild but good flavor.  Certainly better than the other offerings from Coors.
Nice color.  Smooth malt tones with caramel flavors.  Slight hoppiness.

Interesting Nuffield I caught the same thing --a whiff of artificial grape.  Vey interesting.
Weak head, but a nice crisp taste.  Not at all bad for a Sunday afternoon watching football.
Nice copper color.  Decent flavor with a smooth maltyness.  A requirement in Texas lite bock beer drinking.
Nice head.  Malty, sweet aroma.  Taste sweet and malty with hints of caramel.  Overall I enjoyed this beer.

First I must second the suggestion to visit the Big Texan for steaks.  You wont be disappointed.  Not much I can add, definitely a Shiner copycat.  A beer to drink if moneys short and your not feeling adventuresome.
Smooth with hints of sweetness and spice.  Not as strong as other Winters I like.
Dry and fairly crisp.  Slight citrus flavor.  Certainly not Shiners best.
